                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2229" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - we live at the <placeName id="t18290409-238-crimeloc1341">Crown and Magpie tavern</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-238-crimeloc1341" type="placeName" value="Crown and Magpie tavern"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-238-crimeloc1341" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-238-off1339 t18290409-238-crimeloc1341"></join> - it is my father's house - his name is 
               <persName id="t18290409-238-person2230">
                  John 
                  Little
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2230" type="surname" value="Little"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2230" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2230" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - it is in the parish of <placeName id="t18290409-238-crimeloc1342">St. Botolph, Aldgate, and in the City</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-238-crimeloc1342" type="placeName" value="St. Botolph, Aldgate, and in the City"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-238-crimeloc1342" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-238-off1339 t18290409-238-crimeloc1342"></join>. The prisoner was <rs id="t18290409-238-deflabel1343" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-238-defend2225 t18290409-238-deflabel1343"></join> in the house, and had been so about ten days or a fortnight at the time of the robbery - there was one more servant in the house besides her; I lost a gold watch, with a chain to it - it was locked up in my bed-room, and had two seals, two rings, one key, a box and slide - they were all locked in my bed-room, which is one of the rooms detached from the house, but part of the dwelling-house; the prisoner used to clean the room, and attend to it; I know the property was safe the day before I missed it - I saw it all, it was locked in a drawer - I put the key into another drawer, which was not locked; I missed it next day, and made inquiry about it, and the prisoner helped me to look for it - but it was not found; I saw the watch at Lambeth-street office, and the chain, but it was not then attached to the watch; when I lost it, the watch-chain, seals, a ring, key, and slide, were all fastened together, and put in a red morocco case - I saw it at Lambeth-street about a month after I missed it, which was on the 2d of February; my father rented the house - my husband was at sea.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-238-person2231">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BROCK
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2231" type="surname" value="BROCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2231" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2231" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am shopman to Nicholls and Latter, pawnbrokers, No. 80, Broad-street, Ratcliff-cross. I took a gold chain in pawn on the 16th of February for 24s. of the prisoner - I am certain she is the person - she never pawned there before; she was about a quarter of an hour with me - I am quite certain of her person: the prisoner said the chain belonged to a Mrs. Page, for whom she pawned it, and her own name was 
               <persName id="t18290409-238-person2232">
                  Sarah 
                  Bowick
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2232" type="surname" value="Bowick"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2232" type="given" value="Sarah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2232" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , No. 2, Webb's-place, which is in Limehouse; I produced it at the office about a fortnight after - Mrs. Muirhead claimed it.</p>
               <p>MRS. MUIRHEAD. This is my chain - I had had it about three months - I am positive of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-238-person2233">
                  HENRY 
                  HAWKINS
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2233" type="surname" value="HAWKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2233" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2233" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker, of Catherine-street, Limehouse. I bought a seal of the prisoner on the 16th or 17th of February; I am certain of her - she gave me her own name; she said it was given her by a former sweetheart, and having married another person, she did not want it; the officer has it - this is it (looking at it) - I gave it to the officer - I gave 8s. for it.</p>
               <p>MRS. MUIRHEAD. I know this seal - it is exactly like mine - it is an amethyst seal, and no engraving on it; the prisoner left the service exactly a fortnight after I lost it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-238-person2234">
                  EDWARD 
                  WILLIAM
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2234" type="surname" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2234" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2234" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             WIGGINS. I am servant to Mr. Dicker, a pawnbroker, of Three Colt-street, Limehouse. I have a gold watch, pawned on the 21st of February, by the prisoner, in the name of Sarah Page; she said she<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090114"></xptr>pawned it for her mother; I am quite sure of her person- I have seen her in the neighbourhood before - she was about twenty minutes with me; I advanced 4l. on it; it was produced at the office on the 3d of March, and claimed by Mrs. Muirhead.</p>
               <p>MRS. MUIRHEAD. I am certain it is mine - my husband has no other Christian name; I have been married about twelve months; I had had the watch about three months - and am certain of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-238-person2235">
                  JAMES 
                  LEA
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2235" type="surname" value="LEA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2235" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2235" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer of Lambeth-street. I apprehended the prisoner first on the 23d of February, in the room of Mrs. Higgins, a witness who is not here; I told her it was on suspicion of stealing a gold watch; she denied all knowledge of it; in coming down stairs she whipped very quick into the first floor room - I went to look for her, and found her behind the door; I found nothing on her; I took her to the office, and she was discharged: about four days after, Mrs. Little, Mrs. Muirhead's mother, brought her to the office in a coach; I then went round to the different pawnbrokers - I searched her, but found no duplicates on her; I have a seal, pawned in Ratcliff-highway; I have also a slide, ring, and key, which were found by the witness who is not here.</p>
               <p>MRS. MUIRHEAD. This is one of my seals; this slide, key, and ring were all attached to my watch - I know them by the pattern; I went after the prisoner's character, and was satisfied with it.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-238-person2236">
                  JOHN 
                  LITTLE
               <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2236" type="surname" value="LITTLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2236" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-person2236" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep this tavern, and rent the whole premises; my daughter slept in a room within the premises - it was part of the dwelling-house that I rented - it was all rated as one house - my daughter paid me no rent - I could turn her out of the room whenever I pleased.</p>
               <p>GUILTY - <rs id="t18290409-238-punish1344" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-238-punish1344" type="punishmentCategory" value="death"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-238-defend2225 t18290409-238-punish1344"></join>
               DEATH
            </rs>. Aged 22.</p>
